<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920228-0038</DOCNO><DOCID>920228-0038.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- United Parcel Service:   Firm Agrees to Pay Fine   Over Health, Safety Rules</HL><DATE>02/28/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   LABOR X.UPS</CO><MS>INDUSTRIAL (IDU)</MS><IN>AIR-FREIGHT SERVICES (AIF)</IN><NS>LABOR, UNIONS, STRIKES, WAGES, RECRUITMENT (LAB)</NS><GV>LABOR DEPARTMENT (LBR)</GV><RE>CONNECTICUT (CT)GEORGIA (GA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)NEW YORK (NY)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   United Parcel Service of America Inc. agreed to pay a$556,000 fine and to institute a plan to protect workers fromhazardous-substance spills and leakages, in order to settleLabor Department charges of work place health and safetyviolations.   The department's Occupational Safety and HealthAdministration had charged UPS with violating governmentrules covering the recording of injuries and illnesses. UPSwas also charged with violating the OSHA standard onhazardous-waste operations and emergency response when spillsor leakages occur.</LP><TEXT>   OSHA had charged the small-package transport company withrecord-keeping violations at its Uniondale, N.Y., andWatertown, Conn., facilities, proposing $905,000 in fines. Italso cited these and other UPS facilities for deficienciesinvolving procedures for responding when packages containinghazardous substances are damaged.</TEXT></DOC>